&lt;p&gt;Update your &lt;code&gt;Chart.yaml&lt;/code&gt; file to add maintainers and &lt;em&gt;then&lt;/em&gt; it should pass. If you want to disable this check, set &lt;code&gt;--validate-maintainers&lt;/code&gt; to &lt;code&gt;false&lt;/code&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If you&amp;rsquo;re not using either GitHub, GitLab, or Bitbucket - you&amp;rsquo;ll have to disable this check.
{: .prompt-info }&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;h3&gt;Install Command&lt;span class=&#34;hx-absolute -hx-mt-20&#34; id=&#34;install-command&#34;&gt;&lt;/span&gt;
    &lt;a href=&#34;#install-command&#34; class=&#34;subheading-anchor&#34; aria-label=&#34;Permalink for this section&#34;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;p&gt;Once you&amp;rsquo;ve fixed your linting errors, you can then test your changes on a cluster. The &lt;a href=&#34;https://github.com/helm/chart-testing/blob/main/doc/ct_install.md&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34; rel=&#34;noopener&#34;&gt;ct install&lt;/a&gt; command allows you to install and test a chart with many different, mutually exclusive configurations.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I wanted to keep it simple in this post - so for more details on the various options available, I&amp;rsquo;d suggest looking at the docs link above.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;For a test cluster, a good option is &lt;a href=&#34;https://kind.sigs.k8s.io/&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34; rel=&#34;noopener&#34;&gt;kind&lt;/a&gt; as the cluster can be created and destroyed quickly to help with the feedback loop.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;To have a look at a successful lint and test of a chart, have a look at this &lt;a href=&#34;https://github.com/thepaulmacca/chart-testing-demo/actions/runs/11404343387/job/31733302231?pr=1&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34; rel=&#34;noopener&#34;&gt;workflow run&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This will work fine in most basic scenarios - but if you&amp;rsquo;re using more advanced tooling and need to connect to external services for your tests, you should use a cluster in your own environment instead of using kind.
{: .prompt-info }&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;h2&gt;Summary&lt;span class=&#34;hx-absolute -hx-mt-20&#34; id=&#34;summary&#34;&gt;&lt;/span&gt;
    &lt;a href=&#34;#summary&#34; class=&#34;subheading-anchor&#34; aria-label=&#34;Permalink for this section&#34;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;p&gt;Using &lt;code&gt;ct&lt;/code&gt; adds much more advanced linting and testing capabilities compared to &lt;code&gt;helm lint&lt;/code&gt;, so you should seriously consider using it for your chart development and testing scenarios.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If you want to see a full example, please check out this &lt;a href=&#34;https://github.com/thepaulmacca/chart-testing-demo&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34; rel=&#34;noopener&#34;&gt;repo&lt;/a&gt;. I&amp;rsquo;ve used GitHub Actions for my demo, as there&amp;rsquo;s some great actions available to use.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Thanks for reading, and please let me know if you&amp;rsquo;ve found it useful!&lt;/p&gt;

